<HEADLINE>
<P>
BIG EIGHT FIRST SET BY BRYANT 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By AP 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
KANSAS CITY 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Barry Sanders never did it. Neither did Billy Sims, or Johnny Rodgers, or Mike 
Rozier or any other Heisman Trophy winner produced by the Big Eight. 
</P>
<P>
Not once -- until Saturday -- had a Big Eight rookie made his rushing debut 
with a 200-yard game. 
</P>
<P>
Blaise Bryant, who led the nation's junior college rushers last year, rolled up 
213 yards on 27 carries as Iowa State swamped Ohio University, 28-3, in its 
season opener at Ames. 
</P>
<P>
The 6-foot-1, 200-pound Bryant, a Cypress High and Golden West College product, 
said he carried the ball "more than I expected to." 
</P>
<P>
"I made a lot of mistakes, like cutting the wrong way or slipping, but I need 
to thank the offensive line for making my mistakes turn into gains," said 
Bryant. 
</P>
</TEXT>
